    <title>Port workers along the East and Gulf coasts go on strike</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="A photo showing the US dockworker strike" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/37pygfWZdJrzPW5aIeJmd7ohtac=/0x3:8192x5464/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73624635/2175263694.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Image: Getty&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="FZ90mN"&gt;Dozens of ports along the East and Gulf coasts of the US have shut down as thousands of dock workers strike over wages and technology that could replace jobs, &lt;a href="https://www.cnbc.com/2024/10/01/east-coast-ports-strike-ila-union-work-stop-billions-in-trade.html"&gt;according to CNBC&lt;/a&gt;. The strike, which began just past midnight on October 1st, could raise prices and make goods harder to get, depending on how long it lasts.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="Fq5xdy"&gt;The International Longshoremen’s Association (ILA), a union that represents around 85,000 dock workers, called the strike after its contract with the US Maritime Alliance (USMX) — the organization backing port employers — expired early on Tuesday morning. The strike encompasses ports stretching from Maine to Texas.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="ylqZBA"&gt;Negotiations for a new contract are still ongoing, with the USMX &lt;a href="https://www.ajot.com/insights/full/ai-usmx-says-it-ila-have-traded-counter-offers-related-to-wages"&gt;proposing a 50 percent wage increase&lt;/a&gt;. Along...&lt;/p&gt;
